# The Scripta Markup Language

The Scripta markup language  consists of just two things, [index elements] and [index blocks].[footnote Our aim is to design a langauge that is as simple as possible without losing
expressive power.]

## Elements

Ordinary text, like "Happy New Year" is an element.   So are [index named elements], which have the form `[NAME BODY]`.
Below are some examples: font-style elements, math elements, chemistry elements, and code elements.  There are many more. See XXX

[italic [u Font styles.]]   `[i Happy New Year]` is an 
[index italic  element].  It renders as [i Happy New Year]. 
`[b Happy New Year]` is a [index bold element].
It renders as [b Happy New Year]. 
Elements [index compose] so `[i [b Happy New Year]]` yields [i [b Happy New Year]].  

It may seem awkward to type ` [ ` then the text of the block, then ` ] `.  But the Scripta editor helps you: as soon as you type ` [ ` it types ` ] ` and puts the cursor between the 
left and right braces, so you just continue typing.  When you finish typing the body of the element, type `]` again and keep going.  Once you learn to do this, you are a speed demon.

[italic [u Math.]] Write mathematical formulas, equations, etc. with a [index math element], e.g., [math a^2 + b^2 = c^2].

| indent
`[math a^2 + b^2 = c^2]` $quad \to quad$ [math a^2 + b^2 = c^2]

The shorthand form `[m a^2 + b^2 = c^2]` also works.  If you
want, you can use TeX/LaTex syntax, `$a^2 + b^2 = c^2$`.

[italic [u Chemistry.]] Write chemical formulas using a 
[italic chem element]:

| indent
Methane is `[chem CH4]` $\to$ Methane is [chem CH4]

[italic [u Code].] Write code using a [index code element]. 

| indent
`[code a^2 + b^ = c^2]` $\to$ [code a^2 + b^ = c^2]

You can also enclose
code in backticks, e.g., [bt]like this[bt].



## Blocks

A [index block] consists of a bunch of contiguous lines of text with an empty line above and below.  Like this:


| code indent:4
  -------------
  -------------
  -- block 1 --
  -------------
  -------------
  
  -------------
  -------------
  -- block 2 --
  -------------
  -------------
    
  -------------
  -------------
  -- block 3 --
  -------------
  -------------


A paragraph, like the one below, is a kind of block.
Note the mixture of ordinary text and elements like
`[red Erik ...]`

| code
[red Erik the Red (Old Norse: Eiríkr rauði)] 
was a Norse mexplorer and settler, best known 
for founding the first Norse colonies in Greenland 
in the late 10th century. We do not know the 
origin of the nickname "Red."  Perhaps the
color of his hair, perhaps is fiery temperament.
(He was exiled from Norway for violence, later
from [blue Iceland] for murder.  
He died in [b [green Greenland.]])

Our paragraph renders like this:

