| float:left 
| width:70 
| caption:Jellyfish
https://imagedelivery.net/9U-0Y4sEzXlO6BXzTnQnYQ/5c12dfcf-0698-4e0b-733b-f9abf2bfff00/public

| paragraph padding-right:3
The tiny image of jellyfish that you see on your 
left is put there using an [index image block].  Click on the image to expand it.  Click on the expanded image to return the view you ser here.  Image blocks have a lot of options.  Lets begin with the simplest case, no option at all:

| code
| image
https://imagedelivery.net/9U-0Y4s...

It has the form

| code
HEADER
BODY


In this case, the header is the single line `| image`.  The body
is the line `https://imagedelivery.net...` — the "internet address" of the image.

The image block we used above for the tiny jellyfish is a little more complex:

| code
| image expandable 
| float:left 
| width:70 
| caption:Jellyfish
https://imagedelivery.net/9U-0Y4s...

In this case the header consists of four lines, each beginning
with the pipe symbol "|" followed by a space. The first line
of the header is "| image expandable".  Here "expandable" 
is an [index argument].  These are single words that
change the behavior of the image block.  In the case
at hand, it means that if you click on the image it pops to
fill a much larger screen.  Clicking the expanded image returns it to its normal state. There can be more than one argument, but these always come before the properties.

The next line of the header is the text "float:left". It defines
a [index property]  of the image block.  Properties alwyas
have the form ========================================-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- `key:value`.  In this case the key
is "float" and the value associated with that key is "left".
A block with this property hugs the left margin of the 
document and the text below it flows around it.  There is also a `float:right` property. The properties set by the next two lines define the width in pixels of image displayed and its caption. 

###  Math Blocks

 Here is a simple [index math block]:

| code
| math
a^2 + b^2 = c^2

It yields this:

| math
a^2 + b^2 = c^2

We can add a [index label] property to it:

| code
| math label:pythag
a^2 + b^2 = c^2


| math label:pythag
a^2 + b^2 = c^2

Any math block that has the label property is automatically
numbered.  The label can be used with the [index mathref]
element to refer back to the equation as in the paragraph
below:

| indent
Equation [mathref pythag] is the [i Pythagorean theorem], 
where $a$ and $b$ are the lengths of the legs of
a right triangle, and $c$ is the length of the
hypotenuse.

Click on the reference "(1)" to go to equation [mathref pythag].  Press
ESC to return to where you were. We made the live reference
(1) by writing `[mathref pythag]`.  

[i For LaTeX users:] As a convenience, Scripta provides [index equation blocks] and [index eqref elements].  These are 
synomyms for math blocks and mathref elements. They corresond to equation environments and eqref macros in LaTeX.



### Chemistry Blocks

Chemical formulas and reactions can be rendered using [index chem blocks].  Burning hydrogen in oxygen takes place via the reaction 

| chem 
2H2 + O2 -> 2H2O + Energy

To produce the text above, we used

| code  
  | chem 
  2H2 + O2 -> 2H2O + Energy  

See Martin Hensel's [link mhchem bundle https://texdoc.org/serve/mhchem/0] for a comprehensive discussion of what you can do with chem elements and blocks.

### Code Blocks

Below is an example of a [index code block].  Click on it
to reveal it in the editor.  The header of the block is

| code indent:8
| code python linenumbers:yes

Because of the argument `python`, the rendered text 
is shown with Python syntax highlighting. The property
`linenumbers:yes` tells Scripta to format the code
with line numbers.


| code python linenumbers:yes
  def is_prime(n):
      if n < 2:
          return False
      for k in range(2, int(n**0.5) + 1):
          if n % k == 0:
              return False
      return True
  
  
  def print_primes_up_to(N):
      for p in range(2, N + 1):
          if is_prime(p):
              print(p)
  
  
  # example usage
  N = 100
  print_primes_up_to(N)





  


